00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:27.020
In this lab we’ll configure interfaces on
a router and two switches.

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:36.370
This is a single LAN, 172.16.0.0/16, connected
to R1’s G0/0 interface.

00:00:36.370 --> 00:00:41.660
In the real world, R1 would then connect to
other LANs or perhaps the Internet, but we’ll

00:00:41.660 --> 00:00:43.950
just configure this small LAN for now.

00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:45.930
Let’s get started.

00:00:45.930 --> 00:00:51.720
So, there are six main steps in this lab.
1, configure hostnames.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:54.960
2, configure IP addresses.

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:57.860
3, configure speed and duplex.

00:00:57.860 --> 00:01:01.130
4, configure interface descriptions.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:04.330
5, disable unused interfaces.

00:01:04.330 --> 00:01:07.310
And 6, save the configurations.

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:11.609
Instead of going through each step one by
one, I’ll go through the steps one device

00:01:11.609 --> 00:01:15.210
at a time, but you can do it in any order
you like.

00:01:15.210 --> 00:01:22.899
So, let’s go on R1 first.  The first step
is to configure the hostname.

00:01:22.899 --> 00:01:27.249
As you can see, it currently has the default
hostname of ‘router’ as indicated by the

00:01:27.249 --> 00:01:28.369
prompt here.

00:01:28.369 --> 00:01:31.240
Let’s change it to R1.

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:36.469
Use ‘enable’ to enter privileged exec
mode, then ‘configure terminal’ to enter

00:01:36.469 --> 00:01:38.700
global config mode.

00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:44.990
From here simply type hostname R1, and you
can see the prompt has changed to indicate

00:01:44.990 --> 00:01:46.990
the new hostname.

00:01:46.990 --> 00:01:51.560
Now let’s configure the IP address on its
G0/0 interface.

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:57.409
Type ‘interface g0/0’ to enter interface
config mode for the interface.

00:01:57.409 --> 00:02:02.399
Actually, before doing the configuration,
let’s confirm the current status of the

00:02:02.399 --> 00:02:03.799
interface.

00:02:03.799 --> 00:02:06.490
Do show ip interface brief.

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:11.620
Remember, ‘do’ let’s me use the show
command even though I’m not in privileged

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:13.620
exec mode.

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:19.340
Here’s the gigabitethernet0/0 interface,
the IP address is unassigned, so the method

00:02:19.349 --> 00:02:25.400
is unset, and the status is administratively
down because that’s the default setting

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:27.239
for router interfaces.

00:02:27.239 --> 00:02:30.510
Let’s configure it and then check again
after.

00:02:30.510 --> 00:02:34.100
So, let’s configure the IP address.

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:43.760
IP ADDRESS 172.16.255.254, and because the
prefix length is /16, the subnet mask will

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:48.540
be 255.255.0.0.

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:53.640
Okay, now because this interface is connected
to another networking device, SW1, I’ll

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:57.049
manually configure the speed and duplex.

00:02:57.049 --> 00:03:04.219
SPEED 1000, meaning 1000 megabits per second
because this is a gigabitethernet interface.

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:07.020
Then, duplex full.

00:03:07.020 --> 00:03:11.700
Devices attached to switches can use full
duplex, there’s no reason to use half-duplex

00:03:11.709 --> 00:03:14.800
like a device attached to a hub.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:17.300
Next let’s configure a description.

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:21.530
I’ll indicate that this device (interface) is connected
to SW1.

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:29.609
So, description ## to SW1 ##. Now, the last step
is to disable interfaces which are not connected

00:03:29.609 --> 00:03:31.970
to other devices.

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:37.049
Because router interfaces are shutdown by
default, we don’t have to do that, however

00:03:37.049 --> 00:03:42.659
we do have to do the opposite for this interface
which is connected to another device, so

00:03:42.659 --> 00:03:43.689
no shutdown.

00:03:43.689 --> 00:03:49.770
There we go, now the interface is enabled
and let’s check out the status.

00:03:49.770 --> 00:03:52.620
Do show ip interface brief.

00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:59.930
Okay, you can see the IP address we configured,
the method is manual, the status is up, but

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:02.459
the protocol is down.

00:04:02.459 --> 00:04:08.650
Although on a real Cisco device I think this
should be UP/UP, on packet tracer its down

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:13.409
because I manually configured the speed and
duplex on this interface without doing so

00:04:13.409 --> 00:04:16.660
on SW1’s interface, but we’ll fix that
soon.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:22.290
That’s a downside of using a simulator like
packet tracer, sometimes things don’t behave

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:25.470
like they should on a real device.

00:04:25.470 --> 00:04:30.530
Before moving on to SW1, I’ll configure
descriptions on R1’s other interfaces to

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:32.690
indicate that they are not in use.

00:04:32.690 --> 00:04:36.830
I’ll use the interface range command.

00:04:36.830 --> 00:04:41.139
Interface range g0/1 – 2.

00:04:41.139 --> 00:04:46.420
DESCRIPTION ## not in use ##. Okay, let’s
check our config.

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:47.850
Do show run.

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:53.810
Here’s the running config of the device,
and here are the configurations of the interface,

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:57.860
including speed, duplex, ip addresses, and
descriptions.

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:04.390
Okay, since I’m done configuring, I’ll
use END to return to privileged exec mode.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:07.140
Now let’s save the running configuration.

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:11.270
There are three Cisco devices in this lab,
I’ll use a different method to save the

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:15.000
configuration on each device to show you each
one.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:22.670
Here on R1, I’ll use copy running-config
startup-config, and hit enter to confirm.

00:05:22.670 --> 00:05:26.000
Now let’s check if it was saved to the startup-config.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.650
Show startup-config….here are the interfaces,
and you can see the configuration changes

00:05:32.650 --> 00:05:33.650
we made.

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:37.280
Okay, that’s all for R1.

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:41.750
Before moving on to SW1, I’ll make the only
configuration change we need to make on the

00:05:41.750 --> 00:05:44.860
PCs, configuring their IP addresses.

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:50.560
Let’s go on PC1….Click on config.

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:55.310
And notice I pre-configured the gateway, which
is R1’s address, because its the router

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:56.690
for the network.

00:05:56.690 --> 00:06:01.910
Now, click on Fastethernet0, which is PC1’s
network interface.

00:06:01.910 --> 00:06:08.030
PC1’s IP address is 172.16.0.1.

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:15.520
I hit TAB, and it automatically fills in the
appropriate subnet mask 255.255.0.0.

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:19.120
Okay, now I can exit out.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:22.920
Next is PC2.  Click config.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:24.820
Fastethernet0.

00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:31.850
IP address 172.16.0.2, hit tab and it fills
in the subnet mask.

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:34.780
Next is PC3...config.

00:06:34.780 --> 00:06:37.760
Fastethernet0.

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:46.100
IP address of 172.16.0.3, hit tab to fill
in the subnet mask, and exit.

00:06:46.110 --> 00:06:48.900
Finally, PC4….config.

00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:50.300
Fastethernet0.

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:58.710
IP address of 172.16.0.4, hit tab to fill
in the subnet mask, and exit.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:05.500
Okay, now let’s configure SW1….enable.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:06.500
Conf t.

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:09.150
First, the hostname.

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:11.690
Hostname SW1.

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:14.290
Now let’s check out the interfaces.

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.400
Do show interfaces status.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:22.000
This is a command that works on switches,
but not routers, by the way.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.150
As you can see, all default settings.

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:26.680
No descriptions.

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:32.680
The statuses are connected or not connect,
not DISABLED because these are switch interfaces,

00:07:32.680 --> 00:07:35.100
they are not shutdown by default.

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:38.920
The speed and duplex are auto and auto as
well.

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:41.950
Okay, let’s configure the G0/1 interface.

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:45.920
Interface g0/1.

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:47.360
Speed 1000.

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:48.770
DUPLEX full.

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:55.980
It’s connected to R1, so DESCRIPTION ## to
R1 ##. Thats it!

00:07:55.980 --> 00:07:57.770
Now G0/2.

00:07:57.770 --> 00:08:00.830
Interface G0/2.

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:02.440
Speed 1000.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:03.750
DUPLEX full.

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:13.890
It’s connected to SW2, so DESCRIPTION ## to
SW2 ##. Now, as for fastethernet0/1 and 0/2,

00:08:13.890 --> 00:08:18.110
they are connected to end hosts so according
to the lab instructions I don’t need to

00:08:18.110 --> 00:08:20.000
configure the speed and duplex.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.190
So, I’ll just configure descriptions.

00:08:24.190 --> 00:08:28.150
Interface range f0/1 – 2.

00:08:28.150 --> 00:08:34.300
DESCRIPTION ## to end hosts ##. Now, as for
the rest of the interfaces, I’ll configure

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:37.080
descriptions and shut them down.

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:46.580
There are 22 unused fastethernet interfaces,
so interface range f0/3 – 24.

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:51.360
DESCRIPTION ## not in use ##. shutdown.

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:53.920
Okay, let’s configure the configurations.

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.390
Do show interface status.

00:08:56.390 --> 00:08:59.940
Okay, you can see the interfaces we disabled.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:06.710
Again, because I configured the duplex manually on
G0/2 it's down at the moment, but will come up when

00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:09.320
we configure SW2.

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:12.650
Notice the speed and duplex we manually configured.

00:09:12.650 --> 00:09:14.820
This is also a problem with packet tracer.

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:24.110
It says a-1000 and a-full, meaning it autonegotiated
the speed of 1000 and duplex of full, which

00:09:24.110 --> 00:09:27.680
is incorrect because we manually configured
it.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:35.580
On a real Cisco device, this will say simply
1000 and full, without the A. Anyway, I’ll

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.010
type END to return to privileged exec mode.

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:41.420
Now let’s save the configuration.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:43.590
This time, I’ll use WRITE MEMORY.

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:47.430
Okay, let’s check the startup-config.

00:09:47.430 --> 00:09:49.080
Show startup-config.

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:53.520
Okay, you can see the changes we made to the
interfaces here.

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:59.990
Let’s go on to the last device, SW2….enable.

00:09:59.990 --> 00:10:01.900
Conf t.

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:03.080
hostname SW2.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:05.860
Let’s check the interfaces.

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:08.700
Do show interfaces status.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:11.990
As you can see, all the defaults again.

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:17.880
Now the configurations we will make are the
same as for SW1, except SW2 has only one active

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.520
gigabitethernet interface, G0/1.

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:24.680
So, I’ll run through the configurations.

00:10:24.680 --> 00:10:27.050
Interface g0/1.

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:28.440
Speed 1000.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:31.130
duplex full.

00:10:31.130 --> 00:10:37.830
DESCRIPTION ## to SW1 ##. interface range
f0/1 – 2.

00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:44.240
description ## to end hosts ##. Now, let’s
shut down the other interfaces all at once.

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:50.140
Interface range g0/2, f0/3 – 24.

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:53.860
description ## not in use ##. shutdown.

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:55.300
Now let’s check.

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:58.340
Do show interfaces status.

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:03.930
Once again, notice the speed of a-1000 and
duplex of a-full.

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:09.160
On a real Cisco device, this will be 1000
and full, without the A, because these settings

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:12.020
were manually configured, not autonegotiated.

00:11:12.020 --> 00:11:16.230
Finally, let’s save the configurations.

00:11:16.230 --> 00:11:17.510
END.

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:21.240
This time, I’ll just use ‘WRITE’ to
save the configuration.

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:22.660
Now let’s check.

00:11:22.660 --> 00:11:25.940
Show startup-config.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:28.630
Looks like our configuration changes were
applied.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:32.240
That’s all for this lab.

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:33.810
Thank you for watching.

